[[Definition|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=36m20s]]. For a [[Topological space]] $$X$$, we consider the set of all [[Singular simplex]]es, the corresponding [[Chain group]], the [[Boundary map]]s ([[vid|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=51m10s]]) between them, giving rise to a [[Chain complex]] (called [[Singular chain complex|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=37m55s]]). Then ''singular homology'' is defined as the [[Singular homology group]]s, which are the [[quotient|Quotient group]] of the kernel of the outgoing map by the image of the incoming map (that is the [[Homology group]]s).

Note that the set of singular simplices (continuous functions from simplex to space) is most often uncountably [[Infinite]], and so the Chain groups are also infinite. However, the quotient groups defining the singular homology turn out to be finite. (see [[here|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=1h11m50s]]).

See [ext[book|https://www.math.cornell.edu/~hatcher/AT/AT.pdf#page=117]] --
