!!!__[[Homology is functorial|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=1h15m30s]]__

 If we have a [[Continuous function]] between topological spaces, this gives us a [[Group homomorphism]] between the corresponding homology groups. This will mean that Homology is a [[Topological invariant]], and so can be used to study if two spaces are [[homeomorphic|Homeomorphism]].

[[Formal definition|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=1h16m29s]] of induced [[Chain map]] $$f_\#$$, defined as 
[[the pushforward of singular simplex|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=1h28m20s]], [[and extending linearly|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wyWebCsTVGI&index=7&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkkdRttylq7Svmob1gxDgcDZ#t=8m]], and it is easy to check directly that it commutes with boundary map (by using its definition), so it is indeed a chain map.

This chain map [[induces a map on homology|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4M7qJK2ShQ#t=1h20m35s]] (see below also), [[defined by lifting f_* to the homology classes|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wyWebCsTVGI&index=7&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkkdRttylq7Svmob1gxDgcDZ#t=10m40s]], and it is called the ''pushforward'' by $$f$$.

[[Functorial]]ity under composition: [[vid|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wyWebCsTVGI&index=7&list=PLLq_gUfXAnkkdRttylq7Svmob1gxDgcDZ#t=12m20s]]

!!!__[[Homotopy]] invariance__

[[Video1|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HIJ1aoMpRR4&index=21&list=PL7BFF10190F42006E#t=7m]]/[[Video2|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A1ljIoXKAzE&list=PL7BFF10190F42006E&index=22]] [[Homotopy equivalent]] spaces have [[isomorphic|Group isomorphism]] [[Homology group]]s. See also [ext[Hatcher|https://www.math.cornell.edu/~hatcher/AT/AT.pdf#page=119]]. We define a [[Functor]] by finding an induced function $$f_\#$$ between [[Chain group]]s which is a [[Group homomorphism]], which itself induces a function $$f_*$$ between [[Homology group]]s by lifting $$f_\#$$ to the [[Coset]]s defining the homology groups, and showing it's well defined because it maps cycles to cycles and boundaries to boundaries. Finally, there is a theorem that shows that homotopic maps lead to equal $$f_*$$, from which one can conclude (after showing [[Functorial]]ity) that homotopy equivalences induce group isomorphisms between the homology groups.

