[[Proposition|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DE9NqVYUKew&list=PL7BFF10190F42006E&index=20#t=2m]]. If you decompose the space into [[Path-connected]] components, then the homology group of the space is the [[Direct sum]] of the homology groups of the components.

[[Proposition|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DE9NqVYUKew&list=PL7BFF10190F42006E&index=20#t=5m15s]] If $$X$$ is non-emtpy and path connected, then the zeroth homology group $$H_0(X) = \mathbb{Z}$$ (the [[Ring]] of [[Integer]]s). Hence for any space $$X$$, $$H_0(X) = \bigoplus \mathbb{Z}$$ (direct sum of $$\mathbb{Z}$$s, one for each path-connected component). That is, for a path-connected space, all points are homologic (as they are the boundary of a path), and so the homology group is the free abelian group generated by a single generator (the homology class of any point), which is isomorphic to $$\mathbb{Z}$$.

[[Prop 2.8|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HIJ1aoMpRR4&index=21&list=PL7BFF10190F42006E]]. If $$X$$ is a point, then $$H_n(X)=0$$ for $$n>0$$ and $$H_0(X) \cong \mathbb{Z}$$.

